The National Consortium for Synergistic Undergraduate Mathematics via Multi-institutional Interdisciplinary Teaching Partnerships (SUMMIT-P) has been working together since 2016 to revise and improve the lower division undergraduate mathematics curriculum. The key element of these innovations is interdisciplinary partnerships, with partner disciplines directly involved in decisions about curricular needs. Collectively, the consortium has impacted over 50,000 undergraduate students and 250 college faculty from 20 different disciplines and creating course content in 15 different mathematics courses. Materials and ideas generated are being disseminated through national conferences, journal special issues, extensive publications, open webinars, and online learning communities, significantly increasing the long-term national impact of the project. 





The project was conceptualized based on research about the needs of partner disciplines, as identified in the Curriculum Foundations (CF) projecta series of 22 workshops organized by the Mathematical Association of America (MAA) between 1999 and 2007. Each workshop included approximately twenty participants from a partner discipline, plus ten mathematicians whose role was to listen and provide resources. All 22 CF reports, written by partner discipline representatives, indicate a need for mathematics that emphasizes conceptual understanding and problem solving, problems in context, statistics and quantitative data, and appropriate use of technology.





At each of the twelve SUMMIT-P implementation sites, mathematics and partner discipline faculty collaborated to:

better understand the CF recommendations;
determine how these recommendations can be used to improve the content of affected courses;
introduce modifications across numerous course sections;
work with a central evaluation team to measure the effectiveness of new approaches;
offer workshops and support for instructors using these new curricula (locally, regionally, and nationally); and
scale-up these new offerings within SUMMIT-P and through dissemination to additional campuses.



The central evaluation is yielded common data across the SUMMIT-P institutions, leading to more accurate information about the effects of innovative partnerships and resulting curricular changes. Additionally, the project has contributed to the Faculty Learning Communities (FLC) knowledge base while generating a greater understanding of the interdisciplinary nature of mathematics within the broader undergraduate curriculum.


